\series bold 
Newton's Laws and Momentum Conservation
\series default 
 
\layout Standard

In your investigations of interaction forces, you should have found that
 the forces between two objects are equal in magnitude and opposite in sign
 on a moment by moment basis for all the interactions you studied.
 This is of course a testimonial to the seemingly universal applicability
 of Newton's third law to interactions between ordinary masses.
 You can combine the findings of the impulse-momentum theorem (which is
 really another form of Newton's second law since we derived it mathematically
 from the second law) to derive the Law of Conservation of Momentum shown
 below.
\layout Standard
\align center 

\series bold 
Law of Conservation of Momentum
\series default 

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma \overrightarrow{p}=\overrightarrow{p_{1i}}+\overrightarrow{p_{2i}}=\overrightarrow{p_{1f}}+\overrightarrow{p_{2f}}=constant\: in\: time\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

where 1 refers to object 1 and 2 refers to object 2 and i refers to the
 initial momenta and f to the final momenta.
\layout Standard


\series bold 
Activity 4: Deriving Momentum Conservation 
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom 10mm 
(a) What did you conclude in the last activity about the magnitude and sign
 of the impulse on object 1 due to object 2 and vice versa when two objects
 interact? In other words, how does 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overrightarrow{I_{1}} \)
\end_inset 

 compare to 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overrightarrow{I_{2}} \)
\end_inset 

? 
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom 20mm 
(b) Since you have already verified experimentally that the impulse-momentum
 theorem holds, what can you conclude about how the change in momentum of
 object 1, 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Delta \overrightarrow{p_{1}} \)
\end_inset 

, as a result of the interaction compares to the change in momentum of object
 2, 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Delta \overrightarrow{p_{2}} \)
\end_inset 

, as a result of the interaction? Remember 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overrightarrow{I}=\Delta \overrightarrow{p} \)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom 20mm 
(c) Use the definition of momentum change to show that the Law of Conservation
 of Momentum ought to hold for a collision, so that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Sigma \overrightarrow{p} \)
\end_inset 

 = 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overrightarrow{p_{1i}} \)
\end_inset 

 + 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overrightarrow{p_{2i}} \)
\end_inset 

 = 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overrightarrow{p_{1f}} \)
\end_inset 

 + 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overrightarrow{p_{2f}} \)
\end_inset 

 = constant in time.
\layout Standard

